Now I found the key code! Look at lines 1720-1779, specifically `Expression::ObjectExpression`. This handles how `substitute_single_use_symbol_in_expression` traverses object expressions.

Looking at lines 1721-1764:
```rust
Expression::ObjectExpression(obj_expr) => {
    for prop in &mut obj_expr.properties {
        match prop {
            ObjectPropertyKind::ObjectProperty(prop) => match prop.key {
                PropertyKey::StaticIdentifier(_)
                | PropertyKey::PrivateIdentifier(_) => {
                    // ... try substitution in prop.value
                }
                match_expression!(PropertyKey) => {
                    // ... try substitution in prop.key
                    // Stop now because computed keys have side effects
                    return Some(false);
                }
            },
            ...
        }
    }
}
```

This is the problem! When iterating over properties in an object expression, the code handles two cases:
1. `PropertyKey::StaticIdentifier(_)` or `PropertyKey::PrivateIdentifier(_)` - it tries to substitute in `prop.value`
2. `match_expression!(PropertyKey)` - it tries to substitute in the key expression and then returns `Some(false)` because computed keys have side effects

